‚Ä¢	Contractive Stress: $P_{\text{scalar}} \propto |\lambda_{\text{vec}}| \approx 0.095$ (associated with the Higgs scalar boundary coordinate).
The working hypothesis is that the gravitational sector ($J = 2$) provides the bulk modulus or surface stiffness required to contain this net pressure. This is a mechanical constraint test, not a derivation of gravity.
2. The Stress Calculation (v11 Capsule Results)
Using the v11_gravity_containment module, we compute the net vacuum load at the boundary scale.
‚Ä¢	Net Pressure Coefficient:
$$C_{\text{net}} = |\lambda_{\text{vec}}| - \alpha_{\text{flux}} \approx 0.0734$$
‚Ä¢	Effective Vacuum Load:
Modeling the boundary as a 3-sphere of radius $1/Q_0$, the total load is:
$$F_{\text{vac}} \approx 9.22\times10^{33}\,\text{GeV}^2$$
To prevent collapse or runaway expansion, the manifold must possess a minimum stiffness (effective mass squared) at least this large:
$$M_{\text{req}} = \sqrt{F_{\text{vac}}} \approx 9.60\times10^{16}\,\text{GeV}$$
This is the minimum stiffness compatible with the Standard Model vacuum at $Q_0$.
3. The Over-Rigidity Constraint
We compare this minimum requirement to the actual gravitational stiffness ($M_{\text{Pl}} \approx 1.22\times10^{19}\,\text{GeV}$).
The ratio of required load to gravitational capacity is:
$$\frac{F_{\text{vac}}}{F_{\text{Pl}}} \approx 6.2\times10^{-5}$$
Interpretation (Constraint-Safe):
‚Ä¢	The Standard Model vacuum stress at $Q_0$ requires a containment scale of order $10^{17}\,\text{GeV}$.
‚Ä¢	The observed gravitational scale is two orders of magnitude larger.
Thus, the manifold is over-rigid relative to the minimum requirement:
‚Ä¢	~100√ó stiffer in mass scale.
‚Ä¢	~16,000√ó stronger in force capacity.
This is a safety factor, not a derived equality. We do not claim $M_{\text{Pl}} = M_{\text{req}}/\alpha$. We claim the inequality:
$$M_{\text{Pl}} \gg M_{\text{req}}$$
4. Implications for the Graviton
The v11 capsule does not require a particle-mediated graviton to explain the containment of vacuum stress.
‚Ä¢	Geometric Response: The calculation treats gravitational stiffness as a bulk geometric property of the manifold ($Sp(8)\times SO(9)$). The data show that the vacuum stress is contained by the global modulus of the geometry.
